Why SUCI  is  the Only  Genuine  Communist  Party  in India
column27: This is an original contribution to the principles of communist organisation, national and international. The following topics are discussed. An analysis of the degeneration of the official communist parties affiliated to the Comintern. An exposition of the dialectical relationship that ought to be developed between different communist parties. The disastrous consequences following from it’s absence. All these are discussed in relation to the Indian experience, but with international significance by extension. And in the struggles to build up a genuine communist party on Indian soil, the organizational principles of democratic centralism and collective leadership are developed, enriched, brought to a new theoretical height and made up to date with contemporary problems of life and organization. A contribution to the treasure house of marxist theory. An invaluable guide to communist revolutionaries struggling to build their party. An eye opener to those confounded with the withering away of real communist politics.

column2: On the  Steps  taken  by  the  CPSU  against  Stalin
column27: This is the response to the de-stalinisation project started by the Krushchev leadership of CPSU in early 1960s. The cult of the individual, which became entrenched in CPSU and Comintern during Stalin’s time is analysed. The real causes which led to this non-communist practice in the Leninist party warrants a deep analysis. Which is done in this booklet, which was originally prepared as an open letter to Krushchev. Without attempting such a thorough going analysis, and locating the problem in the organisation, one man, Stalin was targeted by Krushchev. It was not only unscientific, but had the final effect of going against Lenin himself. The book warns that undermining the authority of Stalin would open the way for all revisionist ideas to pass of as Leninism. Today this book is still relevant because, it is a critical study on communist organization, dissecting it to it’s elements and displaying what it is not. So, by negative example, describing what it should be.

column2: Why SUCI  is  the Only  Genuine  Communist  Party  in India
column27: This is an original contribution to the principles of communist organisation, national and international. The following topics are discussed. An analysis of the degeneration of the official communist parties affiliated to the Comintern. An exposition of the dialectical relationship that ought to be developed between different communist parties. The disastrous consequences following from it’s absence. All these are discussed in relation to the Indian experience, but with international significance by extension. And in the struggles to build up a genuine communist party on Indian soil, the organizational principles of democratic centralism and collective leadership are developed, enriched, brought to a new theoretical height and made up to date with contemporary problems of life and organization. A contribution to the treasure house of marxist theory. An invaluable guide to communist revolutionaries struggling to build their party. An eye opener to those confounded with the withering away of real communist politics.
